nd Raiders season|2019 (Oakland)]]\n}}\nThe [[2020 NFL season|2020 season]] will be the upcoming 51st season of the [[Las Vegas Raiders|Raiders]]' franchise in the [[National Football League]], their 61st overall and their first in the [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas metropolitan area]]. The Raiders will look to improve on their 7\u20139 record from the previous season and make the playoffs for the first time since the [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|2016]] season.\n\n[[Allegiant Stadium]] in [[Paradise, Nevada]] is scheduled to be ready to use by the start of the 2020 preseason, and thus, the Raiders will [[Oakland Raiders relocation to Las Vegas|complete their relocation]] from [[Oakland, California]] to the Las Vegas metropolitan area on schedule. In the event that an unforeseen delay prevents Allegiant Stadium from opening on time, the Raiders hold an option to rent the [[Oakland Coliseum]], their home for the previous 25 seasons (and 41 out of the 60 years of their existence), for an additional year. The Raiders have until April 1, 2020 to exercise that option.<ref name=\"2019Oakland\">{{cite web |last=Teope |first=Herbie |title=Raiders, Coliseum Authority reach agreement for 2019 |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001018885/article/raiders-coliseum-authority-reach-agreement-for-2019 |work=[[NFL]] |date=February 25, 2019 |accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref> On January 22, 2020, the Raiders officially announced their relocation to the Las Vegas area. This marks the third re-location of the franchise and will be the team's first ever season as the only professional football team in their metropolitan area - the team shared their market with the [[San Francisco 49ers]] during both of their tenures in Oakland and with the [[Los Angeles Rams]] when they were based in [[Los Angeles]].\n\nThis season will also mark head coach [[Jon Gruden]]'s first time in [[2008 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|12 years]] facing his former team, the [[2020 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], whom he coached from 2002-2008. Gruden defeated his current team in [[Super Bowl XXXVII]] with his former team. 2020 will also be the team's third season under [[List of Oakland Raiders head coaches|head coach]] [[Jon Gruden]] since his rehiring by the organization (seventh overall).\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Roster transactions==\n\n===Free agents signed===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Las Vegas Raiders|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Position\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Las Vegas Raiders|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Player\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Las Vegas Raiders|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Age\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Las Vegas Raiders|year=2019|border=2}}\"| 2019 team \n|-\n|QB\n|[[Marcus Mariota]]\n|26\n|[[2019 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]]\n|-\n|LB\n|[[Cory Littleton]]\n|26\n|[[2019 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n|TE\n|[[Jason Witten]]\n|37\n|[[2019 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n|LB\n|[[Carl Nassib]]\n|26\n|[[2019 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n|-\n|DT\n|[[Maliek Collins]]\n|24\n|[[2019 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n|S\n|[[Jeff Heath (American football)|Jeff Heath]]\n|28\n|[[2019 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n|CB\n|[[Eli Apple]]\n|24\n|[[2019 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]]\n|-\n|MLB\n|[[Nick Kwiatkoski]]\n|26\n|[[2019 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n|G\n|[[Eric Kush]]\n|30\n|[[2019 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]]\n|-\n|TE\n|[[Nick O'Leary]]\n|27\n|[[2019 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]]\n|-\n|WR\n|[[Nelson Agholor]]\n|26\n|[[2019 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]]\n|-\n|DT\n|[[Daniel Ross]]\n|27\n|[[2019 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]\n|}\n\n===Players released===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Las Vegas Raiders|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Position\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Las Vegas Raiders|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Player\n!style=\"{{